	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Sam aka Mil, I am not going to pass judgement on you or your opinions, but it seems clear that you are not a parent or haven't been one for too long.  The things You do early in a childs life can drasticaly effect the way they are later in life.  When my sone was 2, he opened doors and even figured out the locks on both the sliding glass and screen doors.  He did it a few times, got in trouble, and learned he is not to leave the house without me present.  Now, at 14, he knows he can go outside, but if he is going anywhere, I don't even have to ask.  &quot;Dad, I'm going out on my bike. or Dad, going to Jeffs house.&quot;  My son got plenty of attention, and is a very outgoing confident kid.  Your right, you don't try telling them what to do, but if you establish yourself as an authority figure they can talk to, that 21 year old will listen to advice.  I did.
				</font>
			</td>

