	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Perhaps outside influences can sway people one way or another but I still do not agree that a game or whatever can &quot;make&quot; someone do something.<BR>
<BR>
It can be a cause of duress in an otherwise troubled mind that contributes to pushing someone over the edge but it still does not absolve that guys mother of her responsibility to get involoved in his life.<BR>
<BR>
The media has the most impact on people who were raised by the media rather then their parents.  I personally was not raised by television although I certainly watched enough of it and the fact that I had a stable home environment is what I like to contribute to the fact that I don't let &quot;outside influences&quot; dictate who I am.<BR>
<BR>
If you want to agrue that she has a valid point about the ability of games and stuff to influence people you may.  However, instead of stopping there when you roll back the clock and try to figure out what led to him killing himself how about rolling it back a little further?  Consider that everyone around him knew he was a &quot;geek&quot; and yet his mother took some very lame steps at trying to resolve the issue.<BR>
<BR>
Unplug his keyboard and take it to work with her?  Yeah, took a real genius to come up with that one.<BR>
<BR>
As I said in my previous post (which I forgot to put my name on) parents need to get involved with their kids lives.  Show them that they matter and talk to them about stuff.  If he broke down and cried over losing his &quot;treasures&quot;, which I think means he was hacked not ninjalooted but either way, she should have taken the time right there to find out wtf he was talking about.  The fact that all she can say is he broke down and cried over losing treasure just goes to show how little she cared about learning more about this game that had such an impact on her son's life.<BR>
<BR>
What did she say when he cried about being hacked?<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Shawn, that's just a computer,&quot; she told him. &quot;It's make-believe.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Sure, it is just a computer.  Yeah, it's &quot;make-believe&quot;.  Did she think he wasn't aware that he was playing a game?  Perhaps.  Personally I think he knew very well it was a game but that didn't change the fact that it mattered to him.  Why didn't she sit down with him and talk to him about it?  I mean other then just being judgemental.<BR>
<BR>
I'm sure she has some sort of hobby and most likely would not be too pleased if she put loads of time into doing something just to have someone destroy or steal it.  Say she likes making quilts and she spends a lot of time making a quilt that she really loves...then it is stolen.  Would she be upset?  Yes.  Would someone saying &quot;It's a stupid freakin quilt!  Get over it.&quot; Help her to come to terms with it being stolen?  Pobably not.<BR>
<BR>
If my daughter ever comes to me upset of something like this I sure as hell won't just shrug it off and tell her she's being unreasonable for feeling sad.<BR>
<BR>
Some people really shouldn't have kids.  She probably is one of those people that have children to fill some void in their personal life and act like their kids are just facets of their life.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
